<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-129-067 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 852 370</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  June 17 1991 v8 n24 p11(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FastDisk speeds Windows 3.1. (device that speeds up disk activityby sending commands to the hard-drive controllers) (MicrosoftCorp.'s Windows 3.1 graphical user interface)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schroeder, Erica.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.1 (Graphical user interface) (Productdevelopment).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentGraphical user interfaceDisk/tape file utilities.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Erica SchroederandM;Microsoft Corp. is taking control of your hardware to improve the performanceof Windows.andM;The latest pre-beta copy of Windows 3.1 examined last week by PC Weekincludes a device called FastDisk.andP;  This feature speeds up disk activity bysending commands, such as Copy, directly to the hard-drive controllersinstead of through DOS and BIOS.andP;  The beta copy includes a driver only forWestern Digital Corp. controllers and compatibles.andM;&quot;FastDisk does look pretty good to me,&quot; said one beta tester.andP;  &quot;From aperformance point of view, it's a good idea, but you have to be real, realcareful,&quot; because it could overwrite data on the disk.andP;  &quot;They're trying toget some of the same performance characteristics as OS/2,&quot; he added,referring to OS/2 1.2's High Performance File System.andM;Microsoft, of Redmond, Wash., plans to release Windows 3.1 by the end of theyear and will include ease-of-use functions such as a File Open dialog boxthat has been expanded to list directories as folders, enabling users toselect drives from a drop-down list (see photo at right).andM;Another new feature in 3.1 is a Startup group in the Program Manager.andP;  Userscan drag and drop programs into the group, which then will be automaticallyloaded every time Windows is booted.andP;  This eliminates the need to manuallyedit the WIN.INI file.andM;&quot;It's pretty silly that you had to get into a text editor to [rearrange thedesktop] in 3.0,&quot; said beta tester Jesse Berst, publisher of Windows WatcherNewsletter, an industry newsletter in Redmond.andM;The beta copy also contained 13 scalable fonts from Apple Computer Inc.'sTrueType technology, including Arial, Times New Roman, Symbol and Courier.andM;While impressed with TrueType, testers were leery of its actualimplementation.andP;  &quot;I give it an A for concept, but it's looking like a C+ sofar for execution,&quot; Berst said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>